      <div class=3D"section section-anchor" id=3D"benefits-of-following-the=
-agile-manifesto" daa-lh=3D"s8"><div class=3D"content" daa-lh=3D"b1|content=
"><h2 id=3D"benefits-of-following-the-agile-manifesto">Benefits of followin=
g the Agile Manifesto.</h2></div>
       =20
        <div class=3D"section-metadata" data-block-status=3D"loaded">
          <div>
            <div>anchor</div>
            <div>benefits-of-following-the-agile-manifesto</div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class=3D"section" daa-lh=3D"s9"><div class=3D"content" daa-lh=3D=
"b1|content"><p>Since its inception, the Agile Manifesto has led to signifi=
cant successes in product development. Key benefits include:</p><ul>
          <li><strong>Increased customer satisfaction:</strong> Agile's foc=
us on collaboration and continuous delivery ensures that the final product =
aligns closely with customer needs.</li>
          <li><strong>Improved product quality:</strong> The iterative deve=
lopment process and emphasis on technical excellence result in higher-quali=
ty software with fewer defects.</li>
          <li><strong>Enhanced team collaboration:</strong> Self-organizing=
 teams and open communication foster a more productive and cooperative work=
 environment.</li>
          <li><strong>Greater flexibility and adaptability:</strong> Agile'=
s ability to embrace change allows teams to respond quickly to evolving req=
uirements and market conditions.</li>
          <li><strong>Faster time to market:</strong> The focus on deliveri=
ng working software frequently enables organizations to launch products mor=
e quickly.</li>
          <li><strong>Better risk management:</strong> Agile's iterative cy=
cles allow for early identification and mitigation of risks, reducing the l=
ikelihood of project failures.</li>
        </ul><p>These benefits have driven the adoption of scaled Agile fra=
meworks like Scaled Agile Framework (SAFe) and Large-Scale Scrum (LeSS), ex=
tending Agile principles beyond software development into other enterprise =
functions</p><h2 id=3D"relevance-today">Relevance today.</h2><p>Since its s=
igning, the Agile Manifesto has become one of the most widely adopted appro=
aches to product development, driving significant success across industries=
. It has also given rise to scaled <a href=3D"https://business.adobe.com/bl=
og/basics/agile" daa-ll=3D"Agile development pr-1--Relevance today">Agile d=
evelopment processes</a>, such as the <a href=3D"https://business.adobe.com=
/blog/basics/scaled-agile" daa-ll=3D"Scaled Agile Framewo-2--Relevance toda=
y">Scaled Agile Framework</a> (SAFe) and Large-Scale Scrum (LeSS), which ex=
tend Agile practices beyond software development and into other teams withi=
n the enterprise. According to <a href=3D"https://hbr.org/sponsored/2018/03=
/survey-data-shows-that-many-companies-are-still-not-truly-agile" target=3D=
"_blank" daa-ll=3D"Harvard Business Rev-3--Relevance today">Harvard Busines=
s Review</a>, roughly 80% of companies are using at least some aspects of A=
gile in all of their principal business functions: research and development=
; production and operations; customer service and support; marketing and co=
mmunications; sales; and even HR, finance, and administration.</p><p>This g=
eneral adoption underscores Agile=E2=80=99s evolution from a software metho=
dology into a versatile organizational framework for driving collaboration,=
 adaptability, and efficiency across the entire organization.</p></div>
